article.headline: Sun mistake turns into NY's game on the line
article.linkText: Sun miscue opens door for Liberty
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- Fighting for a playoff spot, the New York Liberty weren't about to let another close one slip away.

	   Crystal Robinson and Vickie Johnson combined for 32 points in
the second half, and the Liberty dug themselves out of a 17-point
hole to beat the Connecticut Sun 74-73 Tuesday night.

	   Robinson scored 18 in the second half including the game-winning
free throw with 2.1 seconds left after a technical foul was called
against the Sun for an illegal timeout.

	   "I said to myself, 'This is your time to win the game right
here,' " Robinson said. "Me and (Johnson) take a lot of personal
responsibility for this team.''

	   The Liberty (13-15) have won four of their last six, but were
coming off a 90-87 overtime loss to Detroit on Sunday. The win
Tuesday moved them within a half-game of fourth-place Connecticut
for the final playoff spot in the Eastern Conference.

	   "This team is playing hard and aggressive, unlike the beginning
of the season,'' Johnson said. "I feel very confident we will
finish strong.''

	   The Liberty benefited from Connecticut guard Shannon Johnson
calling a timeout the Sun didn't have.

	   Tari Phillips of the Liberty converted a three-point play with
8.7 seconds left to tie it at 73. Phillips then stole the ball on
the Sun's next possession and Johnson, wrestling for a loose
rebound beneath the Liberty basket, made the errant timeout call.

	   "There's not much I can say about it,'' Shannon Johnson said.
"They say I called a timeout.''

	   Phillips added 18 points and nine rebounds.

	   Vickie Johnson single-handedly wiped out a double-digit deficit
late in the game for New York, hitting four straight 3-pointers in
a 3-minute span. The Sun (14-15) led 56-45 with 7:01 to play when
Johnson, who finished with 16 points, began her barrage. Robinson
followed with a 3 and the Liberty were within 62-60.

	   The win negated another career night for the Sun's Nykesha
Sales, who scored 31 points. Sales had 29 in Saturday's 69-68 loss
to Charlotte.

	   Sales scored 23 points in the first half on 8-of-14 shooting.
She had all four of the Sun's four 3-pointers in the period. A year
ago she scored 25 points in the second half against the Liberty
when the franchise was in Orlando.

	   "We can't find a way to finish the game. The biggest
disappointment is our defense,'' Sales said. "You see it slipping
away, but you always think you have the advantage.''

	   Liberty shot 20-for-28 in the second half and switched to a zone
defense to slow the Connecticut attack.

	   "The zone helped us,'' New York coach Richie Adubato said. "We
were tired of chasing all the picks and screens. At halftime we
were sluggish and Sales was on fire.''

	   Shannon Johnson finished with 17 points.

	   The Sun led 36-21 at halftime, their largest lead after 20
minutes all year.

	   "When you miss open shots and layups you're asking for trouble.
We don't belong in this position,'' Connecticut coach Mike Thibault
said. "This is one of the worst (losses) that I've been associated
with.''
